<H3> <TI>   Serb Forces Begin Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802034594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0250 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1802034594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, February 17 (XINHUA) -- Serb forces on 
Thursday [17 February] started withdrawing from the hillsides of 
besieged Sarajevo in apparent compliance with a NATO ultimatum 
to retreat, a UN spokesman said today. 
  "Literally they're moving out in convoys, not in individual 
vehicles," said UN Spokesman Lt. Col Bill Aikman. 
  The pullout of Serb forces came soon after Russian announced 
that it had persuaded the Serbs to comply with an agreement 
concluded on February 9 with the United Nations forces and the 
Muslim-led Bosnian army. 
  Aikman said that General Michael Rose, commander of the UN 
Protection Force (UNPROFER) in Bosnia, "has received information 
from senior levels of the Bosnian Serb government that they will 
have their equipment out of a 20-kilometer zone within 36 hours, 
that means well before the deadline of midnight Sunday night." 
  On February 5, a mortar attack on a crowded market center in 
Sarajevo, the capital of the warring Bosnia-Herzegovina, killed 
68 people and injured over 200. Four days later, the NATO asked 
all warring sides to withdraw from the area and issued an 
ultimatum threatening to impose air strikes on positions around 
the city. The ultimatum expires on Sunday. 

</TEXT>

