<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Welcomes `Relaxation' of Bosnian Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2102082294 Hong Kong AFP in English 0754 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK2102082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, Feb 21 (AFP) -- China welcomed Monday what 
it described as the partial relaxation of tensions in Sarajevo 
after the United Nations said there was no immediate need for 
NATO military action around the besieged city. 
  "China welcomes the relaxation, to some extent, of the 
situation in Sarajevo," a foreign ministry spokesman said. 
  A NATO ultimatum set for 0000 GMT Monday requiring Bosnian 
Muslim and Serb forces to withdraw heavy weapons from around 
Sarajevo or face air strikes expired, with UN officials saying 
no immediate military action would be taken. 
  China, a permanent member of the UN Security Council, has 
repeatedly opposed the use of force in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
calling for a resolution of the situation through peaceful 
negotiation. 
  "We welcome all efforts by the international community that 
are conducive to relaxing the present tense situation in Bosnia 
and creating a favourable atmosphere for peaceful negotiations 
there," the spokesman said. "We hope that the parties concerned 
will make continued efforts to promote this process," he added. 

</TEXT>

