<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   NATO `Fully Committed' To Air Strikes </H4>
<F P=102> OW1902021694 Beijing XINHUA in English 2328 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1902021694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, February 18 (XINHUA) -- Britain and its NATO 
allies are "fully committed" to carrying out the threat of air 
strikes in Bosnia, a British minister said today. 
  According to a BBC TV report, Foreign Office Minister David 
Heathcoar-Amory told Parliament that the NATO's decision was 
clear. 
  And it was for U.N. commanders to determine the nature of 
how 
weapons remaining within 20 km of Sarajevo are to be controlled 
by U.N. troops, he added. 
  He said Russian shared with Britain and its NATO allies the 
same objective of lifting the siege of Sarajevo and bringing the 
conflict to an end. 
  Earlier, British prime minister said the past 48 hours in 
B-H 
had been encouraging. 
  Speaking on BBC radio, the prime minister expressed welcome 
to Russia's plan to deploy troops in Sarajevo and to persuade 
the Serbs withdraw heavy weapons by next Monday, as demanded 
under a U.N. ultimatum backed by NATO. 
  But he warned though air strikes now seemed less likely, no 
one should think the peace process was inevitable. 
  British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said if the Bosnian 
Serbs handed over their heavy weapons on time, it could pave the 
way for a new push for an overall peace in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

