<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   NATO `Cautiously Optimistic' </H4>
<F P=102> OW1902031794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0228 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1902031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, February 18 (XINHUA) -- NATO is cautiously 
optimistic about the Serbian withdrawal of heavy weapons from 
around Sarajevo in compliance with the NATO ultimatum, a NATO 
spokesman said here today. 
  Although Bosnian Serb Forces have announced they are 
withdrawing their big guns from around Sarajevo, NATO's 
ultimatum is still in effect, he said. 
  News reports reaching here said that NATO Air Forces 
deployed 
in Italy are conducting training flights in preparation for 
possible strikes against Serb artillery positions. 
  Earlier today, Bosnian Serb leaders announced that Serb 
Forces will complete their withdrawal of heavy weapons from 
around Sarajevo before the NATO ultimatum expires by midnight 
GMT on Sunday [20 February], or will place them under the 
control of U.N. peacekeeping forces. 
  In return, the Bosnian Serbs have demanded that Russia send 
troops into Sarajevo to prevent the Bosnian Moslems from taking 
advantage of the Serb withdrawal. 
  Reports indicate that Bosnian Moslem Forces have also agreed 
to hand over their heavy weapons to U.N. peacekeeping forces. 
  Under the NATO ultimatum, artillery must be withdrawn from a 
20-kilometer exclusion zone, or put under U.N. control. 
  The Clinton administration has warned the Serbs there will 
be 
no extension of the deadline. 
  In New York, Joe Sills, spokesman for U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, said that the removal of Serb heavy weapons 
was "moving ahead at a very good pace." 
  He said the Moslem Forces were also complying with U.N. 
demands. 
  It is believed that Serb Forces have about 500 heavy 
artillery pieces. The Moslem Forces have fewer guns, but more 
infantry troops. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

