<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on U.S. Stance </H4>
<F P=102> OW1902062394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0450 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1902062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Secretary of State Maintains Hard Line Stand on </F>
Bosnia" -- XINHUA Headline] 
  [Text] Washington, February 18 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher said today that the Bosnian Serbs 
have only withdrawn a minority of their heavy weapons from 
Sarajevo. 
  In an interview with the CNN Television Network, Christopher 
said, "We have information they have taken out probably 50 or so 
of the heavy weapons and we understand that they are beginning 
to move some additional weapons out ... [ellipses] It means 
that they've got lots more to take out. They've taken out only 
a minority." 
  He said U.S. President Bill Clinton would make a statement 
Saturday [19 February] morning on the possible air strike on 
Serb Forces in Bosnia, in which the United States Air Force will 
take part if it ever takes place. 
  "Right now, we're in a wait-and-see attitude... [ellipses as 
received] I am cautious about this. The Serbs have 
disappointed us many times before," said Christopher. 
  "There will be severe punishment if they (Serbs) don't 
comply 
with the NATO ultimatum. They will pay a very heavy price," 
Christopher added. 
  He also said that Russia's decision to deploy 400 troops in 
Sarajevo would not affect NATO's decision on air strikes. 
  He rejected Russia's warning that any air strike would lead 
to an all-out war in the Balkans, saying that the air strike 
would only end the "carnage" in Bosnia. 
  Meanwhile, U.S. President Bill Clinton met with his top 
advisors on Friday in the White House on the Bosnia situation. 

</TEXT>

