<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Russia Warns of `Crisis' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2002023694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0110 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2002023694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 19 (XINHUA) -- Russian deputy 
foreign minister and presidential envoy on Bosnia, Vitaliy 
Churkin, said today that any NATO air strike on Bosnian Serbs 
would lead to a real crisis in relations between Russia and the 
West. 
  In an interview with the Ostankino State Radio and 
Television 
Broadcasting Company, he said he had never accepted the NATO 
ultimatum on Bosnian Serbs as a way to solve the Bosnian crisis. 
  "What is this ultimatum? We are not a member of the NATO," 
Churkin said, adding that it is the action of the U.N. 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) in Sarajevo and the resolutions of 
the U.N. Security Council, not NATO, that count. 
  He said Russia and NATO are just beginning to learn how to 
establish "partnership for peace" and if NATO takes what he 
called "frivolous and absurd" action, a crisis could result in 
the Russo-NATO relations. 
  He also was confident that the crisis in Sarajevo would end 
with all sides accepting a Russian proposal, which calls for the 
withdrawal of heavy weaponry by both the Serb and Muslim sides 
and the dispatch of Russian peace keeping soldiers, now serving 
in the UNPROFOR in Croatia, to Sarajevo to guarantee peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

