<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bosnian, Croatian Officials End Talks </H4>
<F P=102> OW2002032494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0202 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2002032494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, February 20 (XINHUA) -- Bosnian Muslim and 
Croatian leaders ended their peace talks tonight in Frankfurt 
with no substantial result achieved. 
  However, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic and Croatian 
Foreign Minister Mate Granic told the press after the meeting 
that the two sides had become much closer in their positions. 
  They described the negotiations as "very positive" although 
problems still exist. 
  They also said they were more confident of finding a 
solution 
to their conflict. 
  Both sides agreed to continue their talks next week. 
  The two sides told the press that today's meeting was about 
the future constitution of Bosnia, cease-fire between Croatians 
and Muslims and humanitarian issues. 
  But neither Granic nor Silajdzic disclosed the details of 
their talks. 
  However, Croatian Embassy Spokesman Zarko Plevnik said 
before 
the meeting that one topic would be a new map dividing Bosnia 
between Croats, Muslims and Serbs. 
  According to Granic, the two sides will first hold meetings 
at experts' level in the Croatian capital of Zagreb and then 
summit talks. 
  Silajdzic expressed the hope that the negotiations would be 
resumed after three or four days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

