<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   UN Envoy Satisfied With Compliance </H4>
<F P=102> OW2102020094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0129 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102020094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, February 20 (XINHUA) -- UN Special 
Envoy Yasushi Akashi said in Zagreb today that he had decided 
that it was not necessary to use air power against heavy weapon 
positions in and around Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia and 
Herzegovina. 
  In a statement he issued this evening, he said that "I am 
satisfied that we have achieved effective compliance with the 
requirement to remove or place under UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) all heavy weapons within the 20 kilometer Sarajevo 
exclusion zone." 
  Both the Bosnian Government and the Bosnian Serb side, he 
said, had been complying with the ceasefire agreement that was 
reached on February 9 between the two sides. 
  Before making the decision, he said, he had consulted with 
UN 
military commanders in the field, as well as leaders of the 
warring parties in Bosnia. 
  However, he said, "this is only the first step on a very 
difficult road, but we are determined to build on this 
development to achieve lasting peace for the suffering citizens 
of Sarajevo." 
  In the meantime, he said, UNPROFOR would continue to monitor 
compliance and any remaining verification required would be 
completed without delay. 
  "It is my hope," he said, "that the consolidation of a 
durable peace in Sarajevo is an example that will be followed in 
the other cities and towns of Bosnia and Herzegovina." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

