<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Grachev Says No Immediate Air Strikes Set </H4>
<F P=102> OW2102021794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0144 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 20 (XINHUA) -- Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev said tonight that NATO will not start its 
first air strikes against Serb positions around Sarajevo after 
the three o'clock Moscow time deadline Monday [21 February]. 
  The Russian defense minister also told the Russian 
television 
program Itogi that he talked for an hour on phone with his U.S. 
Counterpart William Perry after a meeting of defense ministers 
from the U.S., Britain, France and the Netherlands. 
  "Fortunately, they listened to Russia," he said, adding he 
understood from the conversation that although the defense 
ministers hadn't made the last decision to deal with the 
situation after the midnight Sunday deadline, his impression was 
that there would be no immediate first-round air strike Monday. 
  The ministers would resume their meeting Monday to look into 
the progress of heavy weapon withdrawal and the remaining 
arsenals that the Serb side had failed to pull out because of 
the heavy snowfalls, Grachev said. 
  Meanwhile, he said, about 400 Russian peacekeepers had 
arrived in the Bosnia capital and would be deployed there. 
  The Russian deployment was part of an agreement with the 
Bosnian Serbs, who in turn are lifting the siege of Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

