<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Leaders Agree on Avoiding Air Strikes </H4>
<F P=102> OW2002233394 Beijing XINHUA in English 2211 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2002233394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 20 (XINHUA) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton reached agreement 
Sunday [20 February] to avoid NATO air strikes on Bosnian Serb 
positions around Sarajevo, a spokesman for the Russian president 
said. 
  Yeltsin's Spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov told ITAR-TASS NEWS 
AGENCY that the two leaders reached the agreement during a 
telephone conversation Sunday. 
  "The result of the conversation was agreement in principle 
to 
prevent the bombardments, taking into account recent Russian 
diplomatic efforts," he said. 
  "It was agreed to continue consultations on resolving the 
situation in Bosnia in the coming days," he said. 
  Earlier, Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev said that 
there would be no immediate nato air strike. 
  "After my conversation with Mr. Perry, I understood... There 
will be no strike tonight, unequivocally," the minister told the 
Russian television program Itogi after talking with U.S. Defense 
Secretary William Perry Sunday. 
  NATO has given Bosnian Serbs until Sunday 24:00 GMT to 
withdraw all heavy weapons from around Sarajevo or hand them 
over to U.N. control, saying that they would otherwise face air 
strikes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

