<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Leader Calls Off Air Raids </H4>
<F P=102> OW2102033594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0246 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102033594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 20 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton said here today that no air strikes on Bosnia are 
required at this time but urged vigilance after the passing of 
the NATO deadline. 
  In a statement read shortly after the expiry of the midnight 
GMT deadline as was set in a February 9 ultimatum by the NATO, 
Clinton warned that "all parties should be aware that the 
ultimatum stands." 
  "The deadline has not been extended," Clinton said, "NATO 
and 
the United Nations will continue to monitor compliance extremely 
carefully." 
  White House Press Secretary Dee Dee Myers, who read the 
Clinton statement, said "the vast majority of heavy weapons have 
either been moved from the zone or placed under UN control." 
  She was referring to the 20-kilometer heavy weapons 
exclusion 
zone in Sarajevo. 
  "Only a handful of areas remain outside UN control and we 
expect that very soon most or all of those will be within UN 
control," Myers said. 
  She said the U.S. and allies will continue to monitor the 
situations on the ground very carefully. 
  Clinton congratulated the UN and the NATO allies as well as 
Russia for their contributions in the Bosnian peace effort. 
  He said that "NATO's decision applies to any heavy weapon 
attacks on Sarajevo from within or beyond the zone." 
  On the diplomatic front, Clinton said, U.S. diplomats will 
be 
working with the warring parties and allies and partners to 
transform the potential of peace into reality. 
  During a 20-minute telephone conversation during the day 
between him and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Clinton and 
Yeltsin agreed to send their aides to Bonn, Germany for 
consultations over Bosnia with others from France, Britain and 
Germany on Tuesday [22 February]. 

</TEXT>

