<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   NATO Commander on Possible Air Strikes </H4>
<F P=102> OW2102141394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1352 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rome, February 21 (XINHUA) -- The commander of the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) over Bosnia said on 
Monday [21 February] that air strikes could still be launched if 
Sarajevo is shelled again or the big guns withdrawn after a 
Western ultimatum are brought back. 
  "Our mission is not over, any weapons found that are not 
under control will be subject to air strike," U.S. Admiral 
Jeremy Boorda, commander of NATO forces in southern Europe, told 
a news conference at his headquarters in Italy's Naples. 
  NATO demanded that all the heavy weapons in and around 
Sarajevo had to be withdrawn 20 kilometers from the center of 
Sarajevo or placed under U.N. control. 
  Boorda said that after the expiry of a NATO deadline at 
midnight GMT on Sunday, the threat of strikes from allied 
warplanes based in Italy or on aircraft carriers in the Adriatic 
remained in place. 
  He said air strikes could still be called in if the Serbs 
attempted to move guns into the exclusion zone around Sarajevo 
or recapture weapons surrendered to U.N. control, or shell the 
capital from beyond the zone. 
  The commander also indicated that he could be ready to 
extend 
the threat of air strikes to other areas of Bosnia if the 
alliance and the United Nations decided to deliver another 
ultimatum. 

</TEXT>

