<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Secretary, Bosnian Premier on Settlement </H4>
<F P=102> OW2202003894 Beijing XINHUA in English 2324 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2202003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 21 (XINHUA) -- The Bosnian 
Government is prepared to accept a settlement that is "least 
unjust of all" but would not capitulate, visiting Prime Minister 
Haris Silajdzic said here today. 
  "We have accepted to reorganize our country into different 
units now in order to try and make a comprise," Silajdzic said 
during a photo session before talking with U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher. 
  For his part, Christopher said they would discuss the 
"reasonable requirements of Bosnia for a settlement that would 
get international approval, international acceptance." 
  Silajdzic praised the NATO ultimatum because "it restores 
the 
balance of powers in Bosnia." 
  "We believe that after this NATO ultimatum, nothing will be 
the same in Bosnia-Herzegovina," he said. "Where there is 
balance of powers, there is peace." 
  Washington has been sympathetic to the Bosnian Government, 
which is mainly comprised of Muslims, as the grieved side in the 
22-month bloody war in the former Yugoslav republic that left up 
to 40,000 people dead. 
  Russia, another major player in the Bosnian peace process, 
is 
pressuring Washington to exert its influence with the Muslims to 
accept a peace settlement. 
  However, Christopher emphasized, Washington "continues to 
feel that there should be no coercion on Bosnia, that we will 
not impose a settlement on them." 
  While praising Russia's contribution to the Bosnian Serbs' 
agreement to move away or put under UN control of all their 
heavy weapons in Sarajevo, Christopher repeated his belief that 
it was mainly the NATO ultimatum that did the trick. 
  "The principal responsibility for the good results achieved 
in Sarajevo has to be attributed to the resolve and 
determination of NATO," Christopher said. 
  Silajdzic will stay in Washington until Friday [25 February] 
before leaving for New York. He would also meet with 
congressional leaders in the coming days. 

</TEXT>

