<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   UN Spokesmen on Bosnian Serb Withdrawal </H4>
<F P=102> OW2202041694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0316 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2202041694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Bill Aikman, 
spokesman for the UN peacekeeping forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
said today that by the NATO deadline the bosnian serbs had 
surrendered 260 big guns to UN Forces. 
  The Serbs have also withdrawn most of their heavy weapons to 
areas 20 kilomaters away from sarajevo, and 23 of the 41 Serb 
positions have been dismilitarized, he added. 
  Nine other Serb positions have been supervised by UN 
military 
observers and the rest will be inspected by UN Commander General 
Michael Rose and the Commander of UN Forces in Sarajevo Andre 
Sulairu. 
  The Muslims also surrendered 45 heavy guns to UN forces, 
Aikman said. 
  The UN secretary-general's special envoy, Yasushi Akashi, 
declared in Zagreb that air strikes against Serb positions are 
unnecessary. 
  However, U.S. President Bill Clinton and NATO 
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said NATO's threat remains in 
effect. 
  They stressed that any side opening fire or refusing to 
withdraw heavy weapons will be subject to NATO force. 
  Although the possibility of air strikes has temporarily 
faded, the military threat remains as NATO aircraft continue to 
closely monitor the situation in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

