<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   German Foreign Minister on Bosnia </H4>
<F P=102> OW2102132094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1237 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, February 21 (XINHUA) -- German Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel said today that the NATO ultimatum to 
persuade the Serbs to withdraw their artillery from around 
Sarejevo had achieved its intended goal. 
  On a German radio program this morning, he said he was 
satisfied with the developments in Bosnia which have seen 
virtually all of the Bosnian Serbs' heavy weapons either moved 
to a location 20 kilometers or more from Sarajevo or controlled 
by United Nations forces. 
  But the German minister emphasized that the action was just 
a 
minor step towards future peace and added that fresh political 
talks should be resumed immediately. 
  He also called for vigilance in case the weapons moved away 
from the Bosnian capital city appear in other war zones of the 
country. 
  Kinkel expressed his hope that the progress achieved so far 
would turn out to be the start of a total solution of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina conflict. 

</TEXT>

