<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<H4>   Yeltsin Views Remaining Peace Tasks </H4>
<F P=102> OW2202040094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0325 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2202040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin today listed the maintenance of the progress made 
in Sarajevo and UN control of the Bosnian capital as one of the 
three priorities at present in the effort to achieve peace in 
Bosnia. 
  In a telephone conversation with German Chancellor Helmut 
Kohl, he said the other two priorities were to take action to 
consolidate other safe areas in Bosnia and to urge the warring 
factions to reach an accord on a peaceful settlement based on 
the European Union (EU) plan. 
  According to the Russian president's press office, leaders 
of 
the two countries expressed support for an active UN role in 
resolving the Bosnian issue and said the proposal put forward by 
mediator states to end the conflict through political means was 
very important. 
  They hoped that the meeting of foreign ministers from 
Russia, 
the United States and EU member states, which is to be held 
Tuesday [22 February] in Bonn, would present specific measures 
for solving the Bosnian issue through political means. 
  Meanwhile, Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev today 
reiterated Russia's hope that leaders from Russia, the United 
States, Britain, France and Germany would hold special talks on 
the Bosnian situation. 
  In a conversation over the telephone with his U.S. 
counterpart William Perry, he also suggested that defense 
ministers from these countries meet to discuss specific measures 
for resolving the Bosnia crisis. 
  The Russian television reported that Perry had rejected 
Grachev's proposal to send U.S. peacekeepers into Bosnia's 
Muslim-dominated areas, but said his country would discuss the 
matter with its Western allies. 

</TEXT>

