<F P=100> East Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Meets Premier </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102132494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1301 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng and visiting Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar agreed 
here today that the bilateral relations between China and 
Slovakia have developed smoothly in various fields over the past 
year and new avenues should be opened up for expanding the 
cooperation. 
  Prime Minister Meciar is the first Slovak leader to visit 
China since the establishment of diplomatic ties between the two 
countries a year ago. 
  Such high-level contacts and direct dialogue are of great 
importance in deepening mutual understanding and trust and in 
promoting cooperation, Li said. 
  Meciar thanked China for taking the lead in recognizing 
Slovakia. 
  He said that China is an important country and Slovakia is a 
reliable partner of cooperation and there is no problems in 
their cooperation. 
  Li Peng said the Sino-Slovak agreement on economic 
cooperation and trade signed earlier today will provide a firm 
basis for expanding economic cooperation and trade. 
  He urged economic and trade departments of the two countries 
to explore more practical ways of boosting bilateral economic 
ties. 
  Meciar briefed Li on the political and economic situation in 
Slovakia after it gained independence. 
  He showed his admiration for China's achievements in the 
reform and opening up and hoped to know more about China during 
his current visit. 
  Li told the visitor that China's economic reform has been 
going on hand in hand with political reform, and China has been 
very careful in handling the relations between reform, 
development and stability. 
  In the course of fast economic growth, he continued, China 
has scored remarkable successes in resolving new contradictions 
and problems by strengthening and improving macroeconomic 
control and regulation. 
  He told the visitor that China's reform policies have been 
formulated in the light of China's own conditions. 
  "It is impossible for all countries to follow the same 
economic model or take the same development road," Li said. "One 
country's practice and experience can serve only as reference 
for others." 
  Reiterating Slovakia's "one China" policy, Meciar said that 
the Government of the People's Republic of China is the only 
legitimate government of China and Slovakia will have no 
official relations with Taiwan. 
  Li praised Slovakia for taking such a position. 
  Before the talk, Premier Li hosted a ceremony to welcome 
Meciar. 
  Slovakia's Deputy Prime Minister Sergei Kozlik, Deputy Prime 
Minister and Finance Minister Julius Toth as well as other 
senior officials, together with Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing 
and other senior officials, were present at the ceremony. 
  Prime Minister Meciar arrived in Beijing yesterday afternoon 
to pay a five-day visit to China. 
  This evening, Li hosted a banquet in honor of Slovak Prime 
Minister Meciar and his party at the Diaoyutai State Guesthouse. 
  In the afternoon, Li Tieying, Chinese State Councillor and 
minister in charge of the State Commission for Restructuring the 
Economy, exchanged views with Slovak Deputy Prime Minister 
Sergei Kozlik. 

</TEXT>

