<H3> <TI>   Official Urges Confidentiality </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2202094894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0736 
GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2202094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, 22 Feb (XINHUA) -- Qin Wenjun, deputy 
director of XINHUA's Hong Kong branch, pointed out on 21 
February: The Sino-British talks on the 1994-95 Hong Kong 
electoral arrangements are a matter between the Chinese and 
British Governments. The Hong Kong Government has no right to 
publish the contents of the Sino-British talks. If the British 
side wants to publish the contents of the talks, these should be 
issued through diplomatic channels. The British side should not 
violate the principle of confidentiality agreed upon by the two 
governments. 
  Qin Wenjun attended a Spring Festival get-together sponsored 
by the "Hong Kong United Association for the Advancement of 
Women in All Walks of Life" yesterday evening. When asked by 
reporters about the British Hong Kong Government's declared 
intention to publish the contents of the 17 rounds of the 
Sino-British talks, he said: The British Hong Kong Government 
should understand three points about this issue: First, the 
Sino-British talks on the 1994-95 electoral arrangements are a 
matter between the Chinese and British Governments, and the Hong 
Kong Government has no right whatsoever to publish the contents 
of Sino-British talks. Second, at the start of the talks, the 
Chinese and British Governments agreed on a common principle -- 
the principle of confidentiality, and the Hong Kong Government 
should take this into consideration prudently. Third, if the 
Hong Kong Government wants to publish the contents of the 
Sino-British talks, these should be issued through diplomatic 
channels. If the British side unilaterally publishes the 
contents of the talks, it will violate the principle agreed upon 
by the two Governments. He urged the British side to take a 
prudent attitude. 

</TEXT>

