<DATE1>  22 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Academy of Social Sciences </TI></H3>
<H4>   To Introduce System Reform </H4>
<F P=102> HK2102155194 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1402 GMT 
21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2102155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 21 (CNS)--Preparatory work on the 
setting up of an academician system for the Chinese Academy of 
Social Sciences is now underway and a proposal on its 
establishment is likely to be submitted to the leadership within 
this year. 
  President of the academy Mr. Hu Sheng revealed this news at 
a 
work meeting for 1994 held here today. He added that it was a 
necessity for such a system to be set up. Mr. Hu noted that the 
establishment of the academician system was considered an 
important measure for upgrading the prestige and status of the 
academy in international academic circles, enhancing the 
influence of the academy in these circles and helping realize 
the developmental strategy of the academy. 
  At the annual meeting, the academy confirmed clearly its 
goal 
for further development which involves the building of the 
academy into a national research centre on philosophy and the 
social sciences of a high level and of great vigor with the 
eventual aim of serving reform and opening to the outside world 
as well as material and spiritual civilization. 
  The academy has taken a number of measures for this end 
including the introduction of excellent scholars from outside 
the academy and from abroad for the undertaking of research. 
Mr. Hu said that this was aimed at attracting top-rate 
researchers in order to make the academy a real research centre 
for the social sciences and the humanities. 
  The social science sector in China has given a strong 
positive response to the establishment of the system and see it 
as an urgent need. The creation of such a system, however, 
involves many social science personnel coming from local 
branches of the academy as well from other government organs, 
the military force, higher learning institutions and party 
schools at various levels. It poses certain difficulties in its 
setting up, but with the creation and improvement of a system of 
this kind in the Chinese Academy of Sciences, it is inevitable 
for the social sciences academy to follow suit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

