<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Circular Urges Schools To Use New Work-Hour System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102111294 Beijing Central People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 1030 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2102111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central People's Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] The State Education Commission yesterday issued a 
circular in which it set forth its opinions on the 
implementation of new work hours in schools beginning on 1 March. 
  The circular stated: Following the nationwide implementation 
of new work hours, it will be appropriate for various schools at 
the secondary and above levels to first implement, on a trial 
basis, a system of five-and-a-half-day work weeks, in light of 
their special work conditions and teaching rules, provided there 
are no particular problems in doing so. Schools in the same 
district should try their best to implement a unified work-hour 
system. Provinces, autonomous regions, municipalities directly 
under the central government, or authorized prefectures and 
cities should make unified plans. Schools should appropriately 
modify the contents of their courses and curricula in accordance 
with the guidelines of the new work-hour system. 
  The circular urged educational administrative departments at 
all levels to make all kinds of preparations in earnest in 
accordance with the demands of the new work-hour system so as to 
ensure normal working and teaching order in schools after the 
new work-hour system is implemented. 

</TEXT>

