<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Security Ministry Views Certificates of Identity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2102153294 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1404 GMT 
21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2102153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 21 (CNS)--China's Ministry of 
State Security recently made an announcement on the use of 
certificates of identity for investigators. 
  The announcement claimed that in line with relevant 
regulations of "the State Security Law of the People's Republic 
of China", officials of state security organs in the country, 
when on duty, will be obliged to carry a special certificate of 
identity issued by the Ministry of State Security of the 
People's Republic of China conferred and signed by the ministry 
for use nationwide. 
  According to the announcement, the cover of the certificate 
is red and carries such words as "Detective Certificate of the 
Ministry of State Security of the People's Republic of China" 
with an emblem consisting of two shields, five stars, the words 
"State Security" and a short sword. The inside contents of the 
certificate show the holder's photo, name, sex, unit, position, 
code number, the name of the institution to which the bearer 
belongs as well as the functions and rights to be given to the 
him or her. 
  The announcement requires all individuals and organizations 
to actively offer every aid to state security organ officials 
when they are on duty with their certificate, carrying out tasks 
according to the law and nobody may hinder or hold back the work 
of these officials under any pretext with those found in 
violation of the law being dealt with according to the law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

